Crusader of Brell</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lunaticfringesk>lunaticfringesk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/19/03 12:49 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_eyes.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: ..</span><hr size=1> Quote:<br>
&quot;So when the tank looses aggro they have several possibilities<br>
1. Paladin ... cast a fast stun ... chance for aggro is very very high maybe stun nr 2 .. chance is ultimate high for regainig aggro .. Time cost max 4 seconds.<br>
2. Sk some possibilities maybe not so good as the ones of the Palli but in around 4 to 6 seconds he should be able to 100 % regain agro&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
I do have to be honest...<br>
<br>
The SK can regain agro very quickly and has several options at his disposal.<br>
<br>
While I have no proof but my own observations (and I have two good PLD friends that I group with often), festering darkness and stun are about equivalent in regards to how much agro they generate.  Fest darkness is a 4 sec cast snare and generates more agro then probably any other spell I have.<br>
<br>
Terror of Thule also works very well, and, with a 1.5 sec cast time, I use it often and frequently in conjunction with Fest. Darkness.  Its agro is NOT as good as Fest, but it IS very good nonetheless.<br>
<br>
A mob smacked with these 2 spells with almost assure me of agro and, if I lose agro, it generally takes only one of these to get it back.<br>
<br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
&quot;So now we come to the harder part. The warrior will have to do this part more often than the Sk and the Palli cause they throw their high aggro spells out when mob is incoming&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
Is that the problem though?  If a warrior is playing the MT part, should the slower being before the mob reaches camp?  Hell, last night in CoD, my chanter buddy gained agro off of me (an SK) by tashing the mob before it reached camp.  This was a mob that I pulled with Fest darkness, which, as stated above, is probably the best agro spell Ive got.  Granted, he knows that I can get agro back fast as an SK, but if someone was doing that with a warrior as MT, then I think they are probably making a mistake.<br>
<br>
I guess my view on this is pretty simple--just let the warrior smash the mob a little more, in a manner similar to when tanking a *boss* mob.  Let the warrior set up a hotkey saying--ATTACK SLACKERS! when he feels that he has the agro established to not cause the group any problems.  So what if he takes a little more abuse on the front end--perhaps that is one of the drawbacks of being a class that can take the biggest beating.  The warrior CHs, in theory, should be more efficient than with a knight class tanking, so perhaps that is where the drawback is--on the front end, slowers should wait a little bit before debuffing / slowing.<br>
<br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
&quot;But the Ever Quest community decided that we were now the subpar experience group tanks&quot;<br>
<br>
Sorry--I call BS.  I mean, I dont know if something is *broken* or not, but I do know that warriors make great exp group tanks.<br>
<br>
<br>
Luna <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lunaticfringesk>lunaticfringesk</A> at: 3/19/03 1:00:11 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=glatius2>Glatius2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>will kick your @$$</span><br>  Posts: 876<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/19/03 1:47 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_eyes.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: ..</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I guess my view on this is pretty simple--just let the warrior smash the mob a little more, in a manner similar to when tanking a *boss* mob. Let the warrior set up a hotkey saying--ATTACK SLACKERS! when he feels that he has the agro established to not cause the group any problems.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes, this would seem to make sense.  The problem lies in the fact that against an unslowed mob our better HP just don't last long enough make it work, unless of course you're talking some extremely well equipped Warrior who is nudging up against 9k or better buffed.  The 1k average difference in HP between Warriors and Knights will last perhaps an additional round or two against an unslowed mob.  In one round, if I'm using a 2hs weapon, I have a chance to triple swing, more likely I'll double swing, I might even single swing, and I have no assurance I'll hit at all.  If I'm dual wielding, and sucking up more ripostes as a result, I'll have more swings, but I'll hit for a lot less.  Which means that without a lucky proc, that one round of engagement does very little to my position on the aggro list, if anything.  Even if I get an additional round, because the mob got a bad round on attacks, I'll only be a little better off, barring some lucky hits.  After that, I've lost all my HP advantage if not even more.  I'm basically melting in front of the cleric's eyes.  And if against a slowed mob, the cleric needs to start casting at half health to land, they'll need to start right at contact to land against an unslowed mob.<br>
<br>
This is kind of risky.  It's risky for me, because it won't take much for the cleric's timing to be off.  It's risky for the cleric, because if slow hasn't landed by the time their CH goes off, they're almost bound to draw unslowed mob aggro.  It's risky for the slower, because he knows the cleric is going to be focused on healing the Warrior, so if he still draws aggro anyway, which he very likely will, the cleric may be mid way through a CH and unwilling to interrupt.<br>
<br>
One of the major things you need to remember is, that unlike tanking a boss mob, we don't have a bank of 3-9 clerics standing nearby doing a CH cycle.  Letting an unslowed PoP mob beat for a prolonged period on your average warrior, unless defensive, usually means bad things for someone. <p>The Man in Black: We are men of action, lies do not become us. <br>
